<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Complex Number</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Numbers/ComplexNumber.nb=
" download=3D"ComplexNumber.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i=
mages/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" alt=3D=
"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download <span class=3D"display-i dis=
play-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</span></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The complex numbers are the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Field.=
html">field</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
ComplexNumber/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" alt=3D"C"> of numb=
ers <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/OftheForm.html">of the form</a=
> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ComplexNumber/=
Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"46" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x+iy">, where <img src=3D=
"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ComplexNumber/Inline3.svg" =
class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"=
0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/images/equations/ComplexNumber/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformu=
la" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" heigh=
t=3D"21" alt=3D"y"> are <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RealNumber=
.html">real numbers</a> and <i><a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i.h=
tml"><i>i</i></a></i> is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Imagi=
naryUnit.html">imaginary unit</a>
 equal to the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SquareRoot.html">squ=
are root</a> of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
ComplexNumber/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"21" height=3D"21" alt=3D"-1">, <img =
src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/ComplexNumber/Inline6=
.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bord=
er=3D"0" width=3D"41" height=3D"23" alt=3D"sqrt(-1)">.
 When a single letter <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/ComplexNumber/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"75" height=3D"21" alt=3D"z=3Dx=
+iy">
 is used to denote a complex number, it is sometimes called an "<a href=3D"=
https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Affix.html">affix</a>."
 In component notation, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eq=
uations/ComplexNumber/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"75" height=3D"21" alt=3D"z=
=3Dx+iy">
 can be written <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
ComplexNumber/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"38" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(x,y)">.
 The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Field.html">field</a> of comp=
lex numbers includes the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Field.htm=
l">field</a>
 of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RealNumber.html">real numbers<=
/a> as a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Subfield.html">subfield</=
a>.
</p>
<p>
The set of complex numbers is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolf=
ram.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.=
wolfram.com/language/ref/Complexes.html">Complexes</a></tt>.
 A number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Comple=
xNumber/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x">
 can then be tested to see if it is complex using the command <tt><a href=
=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Element.html">Element</a></tt=
>[<i>x</i>,
 <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Complexes.html">C=
omplexes</a></tt>],
 and expressions that are complex numbers have the <tt><a href=3D"http://re=
ference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Head.html">Head</a></tt>
 of <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Complex.html">=
Complex</a></tt>.
</p>
<p>
Complex numbers are useful abstract quantities that can be used in calculat=
ions and result in physically meaningful solutions. However, recognition of=
 this fact is one that took a long time for mathematicians to accept. For e=
xample, John Wallis wrote, "These Imaginary Quantities (as they are commonl=
y called) arising from the Supposed Root of a Negative Square (when they ha=
ppen) are reputed to imply that the Case proposed is Impossible" (Wells 198=
6, p.&nbsp;22).
</p>
